  <entry>
    <id>tag:www.gov.uk,2005:PublicationesquePresenter/15729</id>
    <published>2012-07-04T00:00:00+01:00</published>
    <updated>2012-07-04T00:00:00+01:00</updated>
    <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fire-incidents-response-times-england-2011-to-2012"/>
    <title>Fire incidents response times: England 2011 to 2012</title>
    <content type="html">&lt;div class="govspeak"&gt;&lt;p&gt;This publication and accompanying data tables were released on Wednesday 4 July 2012 by the Department for Communities and Local Government. The publication focuses on trends in average response times at England level.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Statistics in this release are the latest figures available for England and relate to periods up to 31 March 2012.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The key points are as follows:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="response-times"&gt;Response times&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In 2011-12, the average response time to fires in dwellings was 7.2 minutes (10 seconds shorter than in 2010-11) and 7.9 minutes to fires in other buildings (5 seconds shorter than in 2010-11).&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Average response times in 2011-12 were higher than in 2001-02 by around 22 per cent for dwelling fires and by around 29 per cent for fires in other buildings.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="severity-of-fires"&gt;Severity of fires&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;On average, improvements in fire safety and prevention have greatly outweighed the effect of longer average response times.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;In 2011-12, there were 54 per cent fewer fire non-fatal casualties and 34 per cent fewer fire fatalities than in 2001-02.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;In 2011-12, the average area of damage in dwelling fires was 20 per cent lower than in 2001-02.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content>
  </entry>
